WEBVTT

00:00.367 --> 00:03.046
Look, I've invested
in Twitter, Uber, Instagram.

00:03.117 --> 00:05.382
Why should I invest
in your podcast company?

00:05.445 --> 00:07.479
Well, first of all, it's not
just <i> any</i> podcast company.

00:07.580 --> 00:09.981
It's the Cadillac of podcast companies.

00:10.083 --> 00:12.150
Do people still use "Cadillac"
as a reference?

00:12.214 --> 00:14.210
- Mnh-mnh.
- Sorry. It's, uh... the Maybach,

00:14.308 --> 00:17.837
uh... the Khaleesi,
t-the Leonardo DiCaprio.

00:17.923 --> 00:20.106
Wow. Is your dad always this nervous?

00:20.131 --> 00:22.399
- It's 'cause you're rich.
- Soraya!

00:22.501 --> 00:23.700
I'm sorry, again, about her.

00:23.802 --> 00:25.435
We had a little childcare dilemma.

00:25.537 --> 00:27.237
You know, I think I could
explain the money part better

00:27.339 --> 00:29.139
if I fire up the old pitch deck.

00:29.241 --> 00:30.640
Um, now, uh...

00:30.741 --> 00:31.774
I have a graph here.

00:31.799 --> 00:32.886
- Ow!
- Oh, sorry!

00:32.911 --> 00:34.311
I'm just so sorry.

00:34.413 --> 00:36.113
I just never really fully
got a chance to...

00:36.215 --> 00:37.754
to set all this up.

00:37.833 --> 00:38.965
Uh, so many wires.

00:39.067 --> 00:40.434
This guy. Who's this guy?

00:40.536 --> 00:42.402
Look, Alex, listen,
if I were calling an Uber

00:42.504 --> 00:44.037
and it said it was gonna be here
in two minutes

00:44.139 --> 00:45.372
and that's all the time you had...

00:45.474 --> 00:47.541
who are you and what are you doing?

00:47.643 --> 00:48.583
Go.

00:48.645 --> 00:50.477
<i>One month ago, I decided, at 37,</i>

00:50.579 --> 00:53.146
<i>with a wife and two kids,
now would be a good time</i>

00:53.248 --> 00:55.382
<i>to quit my job
and start my own business.</i>

00:55.484 --> 00:57.217
<i>Who am I and what am I doing?</i>

00:57.319 --> 01:00.587
<i>My name's Alex Schuman,
and I'm ruining my life.</i>

01:00.689 --> 01:03.590
<font color="#0080ff">Synced & corrected by</font> kinglouisxx
<font color="#0080ff">www.</font>addic7ed<font color="#0080ff">.com</font>

01:05.682 --> 01:07.229
_

01:07.533 --> 01:08.820
- Now, who said that?
- Dad.

01:08.877 --> 01:10.151
- And what did he say?
- Dad!

01:10.214 --> 01:11.580
He said what? I'm not...
I didn't hear you.

01:11.682 --> 01:13.115
- Dad!
- Ben.

01:13.217 --> 01:15.518
Let Daddy finish
his super-important work call.

01:15.620 --> 01:17.119
I just thought
he'd be interested to know

01:17.221 --> 01:19.255
that I met this girl on the Internet.

01:19.357 --> 01:21.090
At least, I <i> think</i> she's a girl.

01:21.192 --> 01:22.291
Her name's Steven,

01:22.393 --> 01:24.326
and she wants to meet
in a van in the woods.

01:24.428 --> 01:25.861
Ha ha. I can hear you.

01:25.963 --> 01:27.363
Look, I got to go.
They want me off the phone.

01:27.465 --> 01:28.831
All right. I'll see you in a bit.

01:28.933 --> 01:30.866
Sorry. I'm just, uh,
working on this story

01:30.968 --> 01:32.935
about this alleged murderer,
Wesley Harman.

01:33.037 --> 01:34.537
But Mommy's right... no more work talk.

01:34.639 --> 01:36.772
This is morning family time.

01:36.874 --> 01:38.941
I'm gonna puke up my breakfast.

01:39.043 --> 01:41.806
All right, what's up? I'm sorry.
You have all my attention. Go.

01:41.893 --> 01:43.993
Do you want to see a new
illusion I've been working on?

01:44.869 --> 01:45.927
Sure.

01:45.994 --> 01:47.760
Awesome. Let me get my hamster.

01:47.862 --> 01:49.295
<i>Our</i> hamster!

01:49.397 --> 01:51.264
How do we feel
about this whole magic thing?

01:51.366 --> 01:52.965
Middle-school kids can be so mean.

01:53.067 --> 01:55.201
All I know is,
David Blaine is pretty hot.

01:55.303 --> 01:56.969
Yeah, but for every David
Blaine, there's a Carrot Top.

01:57.071 --> 01:58.506
- I hate carrots.
- Me too.

01:58.607 --> 01:59.939
All right.

02:00.041 --> 02:02.808
Now... pay very careful attention.

02:02.910 --> 02:05.444
As you can see, Todd is in the box.

02:05.546 --> 02:07.246
Oh. Morning, Todd.

02:07.348 --> 02:09.448
By the way, I'm doing a much
more elaborate version of this

02:09.550 --> 02:10.916
for the school talent show.

02:11.019 --> 02:12.785
In front of the whole school?

02:12.887 --> 02:14.754
Whoa, whoa! What is that hand gesture?

02:14.856 --> 02:16.055
Look in the box.

02:16.157 --> 02:18.391
I think you'll find that Todd's gone.

02:18.493 --> 02:19.959
- No.
- No, sweetie.

02:20.061 --> 02:21.186
- He's still there.
- Todd's right there, man.

02:21.233 --> 02:22.170
- Fail.
- Really?

02:22.217 --> 02:23.363
Yeah.

02:23.364 --> 02:25.298
What the heck, Todd?

02:25.400 --> 02:27.767
- We talked about this.
- I have to get this. Don't be mad at me.

02:27.869 --> 02:29.402
He's arguing with Todd.
I promise, it'll be quick.

02:29.504 --> 02:30.803
- What do you mean, you don't like the trick?
- Hello?

02:30.905 --> 02:32.405
- It's a classic!
- He's in?!

02:32.507 --> 02:33.639
Yes!

02:33.723 --> 02:34.640
Harman's in!

02:34.742 --> 02:35.908
- The murderer?
- Alleged.

02:36.010 --> 02:37.143
I got to go. Love you all!

02:37.245 --> 02:38.911
Love you. Good luck!

02:39.013 --> 02:40.279
<i>For the past 16 years,</i>

02:40.381 --> 02:42.415
<i>I've worked at a radio show
called "Cheer Up!"</i>

02:42.517 --> 02:44.617
<i>It was like NPR on Prozac.</i>

02:46.521 --> 02:47.687
I got the Harman story!

02:47.789 --> 02:49.622
<i>We'd been doing
the same feel-good stories</i>

02:49.724 --> 02:52.191
<i>my whole career,
and lately, I'd been yearning</i>

02:52.293 --> 02:54.260
<i>to do something different...
something that mattered.</i>

02:54.362 --> 02:56.162
<i>And so I walked into that pitch meeting</i>

02:56.264 --> 02:58.264
<i>with what I knew would be
a game-changing story.</i>

02:58.366 --> 03:01.934
And it... it... it's
a portrait <i> and</i> a reprimand,

03:02.036 --> 03:04.837
not just of the justice system...

03:04.939 --> 03:06.972
but of society itself.

03:08.276 --> 03:11.777
<i>But except for my producer,
Deirdre, nobody else liked it.</i>

03:11.879 --> 03:13.446
I appreciate your passion, Alex,

03:13.548 --> 03:15.047
but the show's called "Cheer Up!"

03:15.149 --> 03:17.717
not "I Wanna Hang Myself."

03:23.112 --> 03:25.045
<i>And I don't know why,
but in that moment,</i>

03:25.147 --> 03:26.380
<i>something in me just snapped.</i>

03:26.482 --> 03:27.514
You know what, you know what...

03:27.616 --> 03:29.716
I-I-I-I-I can't do this anymore, okay?

03:29.818 --> 03:31.885
I-I can't do one more feel-good piece

03:31.987 --> 03:34.221
about child-prodigy pianists

03:34.323 --> 03:36.323
or gorillas who know sign language.

03:36.425 --> 03:38.492
How many gorillas know
sign language at this point?

03:38.594 --> 03:41.326
It feels like all, frankly.
All gorillas!

03:41.830 --> 03:43.597
Sorry, Akira.

03:43.699 --> 03:45.766
I-I don't want to cheer people up.

03:45.868 --> 03:48.201
I want to engage their minds
and open their eyes

03:48.303 --> 03:49.903
to what's happening in the world.

03:50.005 --> 03:53.039
And I know I'm not the only one
who feels this way, okay?

03:53.142 --> 03:56.042
I'm gonna go somewhere
where I can tell those stories.

03:56.145 --> 03:57.711
Now, who's coming with me?

04:00.382 --> 04:02.249
- You quit your job?!
- Yes.

04:02.351 --> 04:04.284
But what if I...
and this is one of the reasons

04:04.386 --> 04:06.086
why I wanted to take you
to dinner tonight...

04:06.188 --> 04:08.522
start my own podcast company?

04:11.901 --> 04:12.926
Why are you laughing?

04:13.028 --> 04:14.461
Because you're kidding.

04:14.563 --> 04:16.596
You're not kidding? Oh, God.

04:16.697 --> 04:18.531
Rooni, I've worked my whole life
for other people.

04:18.634 --> 04:20.132
I want to do something
I can be proud of.

04:20.235 --> 04:21.468
I want something that's mine.

04:21.570 --> 04:23.236
- Buy a boat.
- We can't afford a boat.

04:23.338 --> 04:24.438
Buy a kayak.

04:24.540 --> 04:25.939
I <i> would</i> love a kayak.

04:26.041 --> 04:28.608
Alex, you're an amazing
storyteller, but...

04:28.710 --> 04:30.610
please don't take this the wrong way...

04:30.712 --> 04:32.412
you're not good at anything else.

04:32.514 --> 04:35.215
I know. That's why I'm gonna ask
Eddie to be my partner.

04:35.317 --> 04:36.917
Second cousin Eddie?

04:37.019 --> 04:38.618
Does he even know what a podcast is?

04:38.720 --> 04:40.921
I'm not sure.
But Eddie can sell anything.

04:41.023 --> 04:42.923
I really think we'd be a good
yin/yang for each other.

04:43.025 --> 04:45.759
He could yang me. And sometimes,
I need to be yanged.

04:45.861 --> 04:46.860
You do like a good yanging.

04:46.962 --> 04:48.094
But no, babe,

04:48.197 --> 04:50.497
you need someone who knows
something about podcasting.

04:50.599 --> 04:53.133
I know, which is why I'm also
gonna ask...

04:53.235 --> 04:54.434
I'm sorry. I didn't catch that.

04:54.536 --> 04:56.069
Deirdre.

04:56.171 --> 04:58.905
Tell me you're not mumbling "Deirdre"!

04:59.007 --> 05:00.574
I've worked with like 50 producers.

05:00.676 --> 05:01.641
She's the best by a mile.

05:01.743 --> 05:02.976
Alex, she's in love with you!

05:03.078 --> 05:04.644
Oh, I don't know about that.

05:04.746 --> 05:06.346
It's more of an unhealthy obsession.

05:06.448 --> 05:08.415
I know what this is really about,

05:08.517 --> 05:11.384
and I want you to know,
I am not gonna touch the 401(K).

05:12.354 --> 05:13.587
It would never occur to me

05:13.689 --> 05:15.956
that you would even <i> think</i> about
touching the 401(K).

05:16.059 --> 05:17.525
Again, not going to.

05:17.626 --> 05:19.226
Rooni, this is my moment.

05:19.328 --> 05:21.294
This industry's about to explode,

05:21.396 --> 05:24.030
and if it does,
it could change the whole world.

05:24.132 --> 05:25.966
Let's be a part of that.

05:26.068 --> 05:28.168
I want to change the world. Don't you?

05:28.270 --> 05:29.936
Damn it.

05:30.038 --> 05:32.105
You know I'm a sucker
for Change the World Alex.

05:32.207 --> 05:33.874
I didn't want to play
the change-the-world card,

05:33.976 --> 05:35.842
but you left me with no other option.

05:35.944 --> 05:37.711
Fine!

05:37.813 --> 05:39.312
Go change the world!

05:39.414 --> 05:40.680
Love you.

05:40.782 --> 05:43.683
<i>So, like Jobs and Zuckerberg before me,</i>

05:43.785 --> 05:45.819
<i>I got my dream team together.</i>

05:45.921 --> 05:48.989
Uh, Deirdre, do you think maybe
you could sit across from me?

05:49.091 --> 05:51.024
I'm so sorry... I didn't realize
we were physically

05:51.126 --> 05:52.459
- Yeah, well...
- next to each other.

05:52.561 --> 05:54.160
Aah!

05:54.263 --> 05:56.496
Yeah, 'cause there's more room over
here, actually, so that's good.

05:57.666 --> 05:59.199
So, what, you hired a groupie?

05:59.301 --> 06:01.301
Stop it. Let me make
the formal introductions.

06:01.403 --> 06:04.004
Deirdre Riordan,
meet my cousin Eddie LaGuzza,

06:04.106 --> 06:05.972
the most in-demand salesman in town.

06:06.074 --> 06:08.041
If he's so in-demand,
why is he in a coffee shop

06:08.143 --> 06:09.309
at 3:00 on a Tuesday?

06:09.411 --> 06:12.379
Because I was just dying
to spend 8 bucks on an espresso.

06:12.481 --> 06:13.914
This friggin' place.

06:14.016 --> 06:15.715
Who the hell is she?

06:15.817 --> 06:17.884
Uh, Ed, did you have a chance
to come up with a business plan?

06:17.986 --> 06:19.886
Yes. I ran some preliminary numbers,

06:19.988 --> 06:22.389
and the good news is,
seems like all we really need

06:22.491 --> 06:24.724
is a solid mic and some chairs.

06:24.826 --> 06:25.892
Now, I have some chairs.

06:25.994 --> 06:27.594
I-I-I'm sorry.

06:27.696 --> 06:30.830
It's clear that you have no idea
what Alex does.

06:30.933 --> 06:33.567
He makes highly produced,
highly edited pieces.

06:33.669 --> 06:36.536
They require equipment and staff
and a travel budget

06:36.638 --> 06:39.105
and just a li'l bit
of Alex's special sauce.

06:39.207 --> 06:40.574
But you don't need to worry about that,

06:40.676 --> 06:42.509
'cause it's <i> my</i> job
to get that out of him.

06:43.612 --> 06:46.102
You say filthy things
without realizing it.

06:46.180 --> 06:47.280
I like you.

06:47.382 --> 06:48.882
I think what Deirdre's
trying to say, Eddie,

06:48.984 --> 06:51.017
is the type of shows I want
to do cost a lot of money.

06:51.119 --> 06:52.285
So, why don't we make a list

06:52.387 --> 06:53.787
of every rich person that we know?

06:53.889 --> 06:55.188
<i>Eddie had nothing.</i>

06:55.290 --> 06:57.600
<i>Deirdre had a particularly
lovely picture of me.</i>

06:57.678 --> 06:58.992
<i>I love the way she handled my nose.</i>

06:59.094 --> 07:00.451
<i>And all I could think of
was a billionaire</i>

07:00.529 --> 07:01.728
<i>I once interviewed.</i>

07:01.830 --> 07:03.530
<i>But for our company
to be taken seriously,</i>

07:03.632 --> 07:05.398
<i>we needed an office
that wasn't a coffee shop.</i>

07:05.500 --> 07:07.300
<i>When my co-founders and I
finally found one</i>

07:07.402 --> 07:09.235
<i>that was cheap enough,
I wanted Rooni to see it</i>

07:09.338 --> 07:10.437
<i>before we signed the lease.</i>

07:10.539 --> 07:12.205
Welcome to the nerd factory.

07:12.307 --> 07:13.707
It's an incubator, babe.

07:13.809 --> 07:15.875
Everyone here has ideas
they're developing.

07:15.978 --> 07:18.108
Those guys are designing a robot

07:18.171 --> 07:20.280
- that rocks a baby to sleep.
- Heads up!

07:21.550 --> 07:22.983
Coming along, fellas.

07:23.085 --> 07:25.151
Those ladies made a jacket
you put on cats

07:25.253 --> 07:27.120
to make them hypoallergenic.

07:27.222 --> 07:30.256
These guys are trying to create
a professional beer pong league.

07:31.360 --> 07:32.826
Hey, they're kind of cute, huh?

07:32.928 --> 07:34.761
Oh, I prefer my men more intellectual,

07:34.863 --> 07:36.896
with larger noses.

07:36.999 --> 07:38.431
So? What do you think?

07:38.533 --> 07:41.534
I think it's amazing, babe.
I'm so proud of you.

07:41.637 --> 07:42.736
Listen, I got to get to court.

07:42.838 --> 07:44.671
- I'll see you tonight, okay?
- I love you.

07:44.773 --> 07:46.773
Al, we got a little problem.

07:46.875 --> 07:48.742
Guy wants three months in advance.

07:48.844 --> 07:51.745
I don't have $10,000...
unless I dip into the 401(K),

07:51.847 --> 07:53.446
which I promised Rooni I wouldn't do.

07:53.548 --> 07:55.348
Yeah,<i> but</i> what if there was a world

07:55.450 --> 07:56.916
where you didn't tell Rooni?

07:57.019 --> 07:59.085
- I tell Rooni everything.
- Yeah, in <i> this</i> world.

07:59.187 --> 08:00.654
Let's go to that other world.

08:00.756 --> 08:02.689
Look, I believe in this company.

08:02.791 --> 08:04.524
That's why I'm putting
everything I have into it.

08:04.626 --> 08:06.526
- You don't have anything.
- Yeah, but it's all in there.

08:07.329 --> 08:10.096
I need an answer, fellas.
I got Pilates at noon.

08:10.198 --> 08:13.333
We're gonna be huge, Al. I know this.

08:16.772 --> 08:17.829
We're in.

08:19.893 --> 08:21.336
<i>A week had gone by,</i>

08:21.386 --> 08:24.471
<i>and I still hadn't told Rooni
I'd dipped into our 401(K).</i>

08:24.550 --> 08:27.652
<i>Fortunately, I was doing a
decent job of hiding my guilt.</i>

08:31.697 --> 08:32.863
Oh. Sorry, guys.

08:32.919 --> 08:35.120
I'm just trying to make sure
it's nice and lean.

08:35.179 --> 08:37.034
Guys, Daddy's a little nervous

08:37.135 --> 08:38.869
because he's interviewing
a murderer tomorrow

08:38.971 --> 08:40.371
for his big investor pitch.

08:40.472 --> 08:42.907
"Alleged," and I am not that nervous.

08:43.009 --> 08:44.375
Is it gonna be on the radio?

08:44.477 --> 08:46.077
TV's better. I need pictures.

08:46.179 --> 08:47.645
Ohh! My own daughter.

08:47.747 --> 08:50.181
You don't need pictures.
Are you kidding me?

08:50.283 --> 08:52.550
Here. I'll tell you what.
Close your eyes for a second.

08:52.652 --> 08:56.520
Now imagine hearing
a really creepy old guy's voice.

08:56.622 --> 08:58.856
"My name is Wesley Harman,

08:58.958 --> 09:00.358
and I didn't do it!"

09:00.460 --> 09:01.392
Didn't do what?

09:01.494 --> 09:03.394
Oh! See, Daddy's got you listening now.

09:03.496 --> 09:05.229
Now we hear a woman's voice.

09:05.331 --> 09:06.931
She says she's Harman's neighbor.

09:07.033 --> 09:08.699
"Something was always off with him."

09:09.902 --> 09:12.203
"Always alone on his family's estate.

09:12.305 --> 09:14.739
And when kids would come
and take his apples,

09:14.841 --> 09:16.006
you know what he would do?

09:16.109 --> 09:17.908
He'd chase them off with a shotgun."

09:18.010 --> 09:20.211
Are you sure this story's
appropriate for children?

09:20.313 --> 09:21.812
Okay, calm down, Grandma.

09:21.914 --> 09:25.249
Then, we hear a
policeman's voice on a CB radio.

09:25.351 --> 09:27.918
"Uh, dispatch, we got two murdered kids

09:28.020 --> 09:29.320
on the Harman property."

09:29.422 --> 09:31.355
Yeah, actually, Al,
where are you going with this?

09:31.457 --> 09:33.491
- I like it.
- Me too. Then...

09:33.593 --> 09:36.260
"We now go to Bob Jenkins,
reporting live at the scene."

09:36.362 --> 09:39.964
"Uh, the children both had
a rare poison in their stomachs

09:40.066 --> 09:42.099
and... apples."

09:43.736 --> 09:44.935
- Hold that for a second.
- Ugh!

09:45.037 --> 09:46.637
So, Harman's arrested
and let out on bail.

09:46.739 --> 09:48.506
Now we're in a science lab...

09:51.911 --> 09:54.645
...where a scientist tells us
about this rare poison.

09:54.747 --> 09:56.147
The one Harman put on the apples?

09:56.249 --> 09:58.449
The one <i> someone</i> put on the apples.

09:58.551 --> 09:59.884
The scientist says...

09:59.986 --> 10:01.485
"It's very hard to make.

10:01.587 --> 10:04.789
Uh, you need seeds from
the Croatian Rhine Poppy...

10:04.891 --> 10:07.258
virtually nonexistent in the U.S."

10:07.360 --> 10:09.264
Now we hear this.
Make this noise with me.

10:13.533 --> 10:16.167
The wind blowing through a field.

10:17.136 --> 10:19.032
A knock on a heavy door.

10:19.118 --> 10:21.369
And a voice we've heard before.

10:21.472 --> 10:23.138
"Can I help you?"

10:23.240 --> 10:25.707
- Who is it?
- Harman's brother, Max.

10:25.809 --> 10:29.377
And the wind we're hearing
is blowing through a giant field

10:29.480 --> 10:35.217
of Croatian Rhine Poppies
right in Max Harman's backyard!

10:35.319 --> 10:36.618
So, Wesley Harman's innocent?

10:36.720 --> 10:38.553
I believe that Max framed Wesley

10:38.655 --> 10:40.355
to cut him out of the family fortune.

10:40.457 --> 10:43.024
And I want to tell his story
to the world...

10:43.126 --> 10:44.559
and lots of other stories, too.

10:44.661 --> 10:47.195
And once in a while, sometimes,

10:47.297 --> 10:49.064
they might even change someone's life.

10:49.166 --> 10:50.298
- Whoa.
- Yeah.

10:50.400 --> 10:51.733
"Whoa," indeed.

10:51.835 --> 10:54.402
See? You don't need pictures, okay?

10:54.505 --> 10:55.737
Okay.

